A group, Concerned Shiriro Youths in Niger State has lamented the incessant bandits’ attacks in their area amidst the threat posed by the coronavirus pandemic globally. The youths, therefore, called on the federal and state governments to take drastic action to stop banditry to discourage their people from taking laws into their hands in attempts  to check the incessant attacks. The co- convener of the Concerned Shiroro Youths, Alhaji Ibrahim Bello, made this known while addressing journalists in Minna, yesterday. According to him, “let it be known that Shiroro local government area is facing its biggest security threat since time immemorial. We therefore call on the government to rise to its biding of protecting lives and properties as further escalation will be interpreted to mean dereliction of responsibilities and total neglect of Shiroro local government area by the appropriate authorities ” . Bella added  that “For the umpteenth time I’m saying we are helpless, hopeless, and helpless”  recalling  that the youths have consistently drawn the attention of government at all levels to the plight of Shiroro people He therefore posited that  ” May we state emphatically that in the next two weeks, if something tangible is not urgently and holistically done by government to address these insecurity challenges, as it concerns  Shiroro youths, we shall be left with no option than mobilizing our people to henceforth abdicate from any civic responsibilities”. Ibrahim said that Shiroro people have a long history of peace and tolerance, saying that “our people are law abiding and accommodating. It is worrisome that criminal elements are exploiting our disposition to hunt and hurt our defenseless citizens”. He maintained that all formal and informal avenues were created to reach out to the government to rise to its primary responsibility and the government severally assured the people of security but the attacks by bandits continued. 